{"title_page": "Kings Heath", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name            = Kings Heath\n|country                  = England \n|region                   = West Midlands\n|static_image             =High Street Kings Heath, The Station Pub on the Left - geograph.org.uk - 1283548.jpg\n|static_image_caption     =Kings Heath High Street\n|population               =\n|os_grid_reference        = SP073815\n|coordinates              = {{coord|52.43143|-1.89406|display=inline,title}}\n|post_town                = BIRMINGHAM\n|postcode_area            = B\n|postcode_district        = B14\n|dial_code                = 0121\n|constituency_westminster =\n|civil_parish             =\n|metropolitan_borough     = [[Birmingham]]\n|metropolitan_county      = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n}}\n'''Kings Heath''' (historically, and still occasionally '''King's Heath''') is a suburb of south [[Birmingham]], England, five miles south of the city centre. It is the next suburb south from [[Moseley]] on the [[A435 road|A435, Alcester road]].\n\n==History==\nKings Heath came into being as a village in the 18th century when improvements to the [[Alcester]] to [[Birmingham]] road acted as a catalyst for the development of new houses and farms. Prior to this, the area was largely uninhabited wasteland run by the Royal Borough of [[Kings Norton]].\n\nThe streets running off High Street are dominated by pre-1919 terraced, owner-occupied housing.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nA number of independent shops have taken advantage of comparatively cheap rents in the side roads off High Street, leading to an influx of boutiques and the start of an (organic) [[coffee culture|caf\u00e9 culture]]. In 2008, the businesses agreed to establish a [[Business Improvement District]], which top-slices a proportion of their local business taxes to go directly into improvements and promotion of the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enjoykingsheath.com/the-business-plan-for-2018-2023-kings-heath-bid.html |title=The Business Plan for 2018\u20132023 Kings Heath BID |date=June 2019 |work=Enjoy Kings Heath |access-date=6 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe local community still refers to Kings Heath as a \"village\" even though it has been part of Birmingham for over a century. Its centre at the High Street / Vicarage Road junction has been developed to form an attractive public square which is used as a venue for a monthly [[farmers' market]] and other events.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allsaintscentrekh.co.uk/village-square/ |title=Village Square |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=All Saints Centre Kings Heath |publisher=All Saints Community Development Company |access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 2005, Kings Heath was hit by a major (by European standards) [[Birmingham Tornado (UK)|tornado]] which damaged several shops on High Street and All Saints' Church. The tornado then moved on to damage many houses in [[Balsall Heath]]. There were no fatalities.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Kings Heath Police Station - High Street, Kings Heath (32499828654).jpg|thumb|Kings Heath Police Station]]\nKings Heath has several schools including Colmore Infant, Nursery and Primary School, St. Dunstan's Catholic Primary School, Kings Heath Primary School, [[Kings Heath Boys]], [[Wheelers Lane Technology College]], [[King Edward VI Camp Hill School for Boys]], [[King Edward VI Camp Hill School for Girls]] and [[Bishop Challoner Catholic College]].\n\n==Public transport==\nKings Heath is serviced by [[National Express West Midlands]]' bus routes [[West Midlands bus route 11|11]] (Birmingham Outer Circle), 35 (central Birmingham \u2013 [[Hawkesley]]) and [[West Midlands bus route 50|50]] (central Birmingham \u2013 [[Druids Heath]]).\n\n==Features==\nThe central shopping area runs along High Street and Alcester Road, and the shops include branches of national [[chain store]]s, [[charity shop]]s, supermarkets, electrical retailers and opticians. There are also a number of [[pub]]s, churches and schools on and around High Street.\n\n[[File:UB40 first gig.jpg|thumb|left|Plaque marking UB40's first gig.]]\n\nKings Heath has two parks: [[Kings Heath Park]], which is famous as the setting for the popular [[Associated Television|ATV]] series ''Gardening Today'',<ref name=ATV>{{cite web|first=Roddy |last=Buxton |title=Studio One |url=http://www.transdiffusion.org/emc/studioone/atvs_television.php |accessdate=12 April 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108142319/http://www.transdiffusion.org/emc/studioone/atvs_television.php |archivedate= 8 January 2008 }}</ref> and Highbury Park, which is adjacent to [[Highbury, Birmingham|Highbury Hall]], a former residence of [[Joseph Chamberlain]]. Kings Heath Park has [[Green Flag Award|\"Green Flag\"]] status. It features a [[Victorian era|Victorian]]-styled [[tea room]] and is the venue for the annual Gardener's Weekend Show, which comes under the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] and is one of the top regional events for gardening enthusiasts to show off their vegetables, floral displays, etc.\n\nThe Hare and Hounds public house, in Kings Heath High Street, was the location of the first concert by [[UB40]] on 9 February 1979, which is commemorated by a [[PRS for Music]] plaque. The pub was rebuilt in 1907, but is Grade II listed, as it has retained many original Art Nouveau internal fixtures.  The pub is still an important local music venue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hare and Hounds, The Venue|url=http://hareandhoundskingsheath.co.uk/the-venue/|publisher=Hare and Hounds|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Sport and leisure==\n[[Kings Heath Stadium]] was a [[Greyhound racing|greyhound track]] that existed from the 1920s until its closure in 1971.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tarter|first=P Howard|title=Greyhound Racing Encyclopedia|page =62|year=1949|publisher=Fleet Publishing Company Ltd}}</ref> The site was first developed in 1923 at Alcester Lane's End on the southern outskirts of Kings Heath as the venue for the annual Kings Heath [[Horse Show]]. The ground was converted to include a greyhound track and the first dog race took place in May 1927. After the Horse Show moved elsewhere in the 1960s, the ground was exclusively used for greyhound racing until being permanently closed in 1971. The land was eventually sold for housing development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsheathhistory.co.uk/content/KH_Horse_Show_Dog_Track.pdf |title=King's Heath Horse Show & Kings Heath Greyhound Stadium |first=Gail |last=Pittaway |work=King's Heath Local History Society |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn 18-hole [[golf course]] opened in 1926 just to the south of the race track along the Alcester Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mytimeactive.co.uk/golf/cocks-moors-woods-golf-course |title=Cocks Moors Woods Golf Course |work=Mytime Active |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> This is also the site of the modern Cocks Moors Woods [[leisure centre|sports and leisure centre]], the largest of its kind in south Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghamleisure.com/cocks_moors_woods |title=Welcome to Cocks Moors Woods Leisure Centre |work=Birmingham Community Leisure Trust |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nKings Heath Baths was an indoor facility on Institute Road that first opened on 15 August 1923. For many years, the swimming pool was drained and floored over during the winter so it could be used as a dance hall, with additional badminton courts also provided.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.bathsandwashhouses.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/City-of-Birmingham-Baths-Department-1851-1951.pdf |title=The City of Birmingham Baths Department 1851-1951 |author=J. Moth |year=1951 |publisher=James Upton |page=32}}</ref> The baths closed in 1987 and the building was subsequently demolished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moseleyb13.com/2016/08/04/lost-moseley-last-splash-part-one-lidos-baths/ |title=Lost Moseley: \u2018Last Splash?\u2019 Part One \u2013 Lidos & Baths |date=4 August 2016 |first=Mark  |last=Baxter |work=Moseley B13 magazine |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Kingsway Cinema opened on High Street in March 1925 and remained open for more than fifty years until its closure in May 1980. The cinema was later converted into a [[Bingo (United Kingdom)|bingo hall]], first run by Essoldo Bingo, then [[Gala Bingo]], but eventually closed in 2007. The building was largely destroyed by a fire on 17 September 2011.<ref name=KHLHS_KingswayCinema>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsheathhistory.co.uk/content/Kingsway.pdf |title=Kingsway Cinema Story |first=Bob |last=Blackham |date=July 2019 |work=King's Heath Local History Society |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> It was auctioned off in 2016 to a local building development company<ref name=Mail_KingswayCinema>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/business/new-plans-restore-historic-fire-14169674 |title=New plans to restore historic former Kings Heath cinema |first=Tamlyn |last=Jones |newspaper=[[Birmingham Mail]] |date=18 January 2018|access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> and demolition work was carried out at the rear of the building in early 2018.<ref name=KHLHS_KingswayCinema /> The [[Listed building#Locally listed buildings|Grade A locally listed]] [[facade]] at the front was largely unaffected by the 2011 fire and the redevelopment plans include restoring this to its former glory.<ref name=Mail_KingswayCinema />\n\n==Notable residents==\n;People born in Kings Heath\n* [[Tommy Green (footballer, born 1873)|Tommy Green]] (1873\u20131921), footballer who played for [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n* Sydney S. Guy (1885\u20131971), founder of [[Guy Motors]]\n* [[Albert Gardner]] (1887\u20131923), footballer who played for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n* [[Frank Bowden (footballer)|Frank Bowden]] (1904\u2013?), footballer who played for Birmingham City and [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n* [[Edna Iles]] (1905\u20132003), classical pianist\n* [[Jim Roberts (architect)|Jim Roberts]] (born 1922), architect whose works included the [[Rotunda (Birmingham)|Rotunda]] in central Birmingham\n* [[Peter Aldis]] (1927\u20132008), footballer who played for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n* [[Ann Jones (tennis)|Ann Jones]] (born 1938),<ref name=KHLHS_famous>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsheathhistory.co.uk/fame.htm |title=Famous former residents of King's Heath |work=King's Heath Local History Society |access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref> tennis player who won seven [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] Championships\n* [[Martin Barre]] (born 1946), guitarist for [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]]\n* [[Dave Latchford]] (born 1948), footballer who played for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n* [[Bob Latchford]] (born 1951), footballer who played for Birmingham City, [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[England national football team|England]]\n* [[Peter Latchford]] (born 1952), footballer who played for [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n* [[Toyah Willcox]] (born 1958), musician and actress\n* [[Dave Linney]] (born 1961), footballer who played for [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]]\n* [[Gary Childs]] (born 1964), footballer for [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] and [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n* [[Kevin Ashley]] (born 1968), footballer who played for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n* [[Laura Mvula]] (born 1986), soul singer/songwriter\n\n;Notable residents\n* [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] (1892\u20131973),<ref name=KHLHS_famous /> moved to Kings Heath to live with his grandparents in 1895\n* [[Anthony E. Pratt]] (1903\u20131994),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/plaque-erected-kings-heath-cluedo-1325186|title=Plaque to be erected for Kings Heath Cluedo inventor Anthony Pratt|newspaper=Birmingham Mail|author=Mike Lockley|date=17 February 2013}}</ref> inventor of the board game ''[[Cluedo]]''\n* [[Tommy Godwin (cyclist born 1920)|Tommy Godwin]] (1920\u20132012),<ref name=KHLHS_famous /> international cyclist who ran a cycle shop in Kings Heath from 1950 to 1986\n* [[Judith Cutler]] (born 1946), crime fiction writer\n* [[Stuart Linnell]] MBE (born 1947 in Northfield, Birmingham), radio and TV presenter\n* [[Trevor Burton]] (born 1949), guitarist and founding member of [[The Move]]\n* [[Paul Dyson]] (born 1959), footballer for [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] who ran a sports shop in Kings Heath after his retirement\n* [[Jo Lycett]] (born 1988),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://birmingham.livingmag.co.uk/joe-lycett/ |title=Joe Lycett |work=Birmingham Living magazine |access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> British comedian\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Church Musicians window, King's Heath, Birmingham.JPG|thumb|The church musicians window; Kings Heath Methodist Church; featuring Bach, Charles Wesley, Handel and the local organist Leslie Wright]]\nThe 2011 musical film ''[[Turbulence (2011 film)|Turbulence]]'' was shot in the area, with much of the film's action taking place in the Hare & Hounds pub.<ref>{{cite news |last=Suart |first=Paul |date=15 July 2011 |title=Kings Heath film maker turns to bike power for new movie |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/kings-heath-film-maker-turns-157823 |work=Birmingham Mail |publisher=Trinity Mirror Midlands |access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 song \"Green Garden\" by Birmingham born [[Laura Mvula]] is an elegy to her home in Kings Heath.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/music/|title=Latest Birmingham and West Midlands news on Food & Drink, Nostalgia, Fashion,|website=www.birminghampost.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe BBC documentary ''Fighting For Air'', about suburban air pollution, was filmed in Kings Heath in 2017 and broadcast on BBC2 on 10 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kingsheathforum.org.uk/2018/01/08/fighting-for-air-bbc2-documentary-broadcast-10-january-2017/|title=\u2018Fighting For Air\u2019 BBC2 documentary broadcast 10 January 2018|work=Kings Heath Residents' Forum|date=8 January 2018|access-date=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moseley and Kings Heath (ward)|Moseley and Kings Heath ward]]\n* [[Brandwood (ward)|Brandwood ward]]\n* [[Ritz Ballroom, Kings Heath]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/ Birmingham City Council]\n*[http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/cs/Satellite?c=Page&childpagename=Lib-Kings-Heath%2FPageLayout&cid=1223092586607&pagename=BCC%2FCommon%2FWrapper%2FWrapper History of Kings Heath]\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.asp?sheetid=10125&ox=2349&oy=2425&zm=4 1884 Ordnance Survey map of King's Heath]\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.asp?sheetid=9257&ox=1400&oy=1275&zm=2&czm=2&x=189&y=177 1887 Ordnance Survey map of King's Heath]\n\n{{Areas of Birmingham}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Refimprove|date=June 2010}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|official_name            = Kings Heath\n|country                  = England, UK\n|region                   = West Midlands\n|static_image             =High Street Kings Heath, The Station Pub on the Left - geograph.org.uk - 1283548.jpg\n|static_image_caption     =Kings Heath High Street\n|population               =\n|os_grid_reference        = SP073815\n|coordinates              = {{coord|52.43143|-1.89406|display=inline,title}}\n|post_town                = BIRMINGHAM\n|postcode_area            = B\n|postcode_district        = B14\n|dial_code                = 0121\n|constituency_westminster =\n|civil_parish             =\n|metropolitan_borough     = [[Birmingham]]\n|metropolitan_county      = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]]\n}}\n'''Kings Heath''' (historically, and still occasionally '''King's Heath''') is a suburb of south [[Birmingham]], England, five miles south of the city centre. It is the next suburb south from [[Moseley]] on the [[A435 road|A435, Alcester road]].\n\n==History==\nKings Heath came into being as a village in the 18th century when improvements to the [[Alcester]] to [[Birmingham]] road acted as a catalyst for the development of new houses and farms. Prior to this, the area was largely uninhabited wasteland run by the Royal Borough of [[Kings Norton]].\n\nThe streets running off High Street are dominated by pre-1919 terraced, owner-occupied housing.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}}\n\nA number of independent shops have taken advantage of comparatively cheap rents in the side roads off High Street, leading to an influx of boutiques and the start of an (organic) [[coffee culture|caf\u00e9 culture]]. In 2008, the businesses agreed to establish a [[Business Improvement District]], which top-slices a proportion of their local business taxes to go directly into improvements and promotion of the area.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.enjoykingsheath.com/the-business-plan-for-2018-2023-kings-heath-bid.html |title=The Business Plan for 2018\u20132023 Kings Heath BID |date=June 2019 |work=Enjoy Kings Heath |access-date=6 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe local community still refers to Kings Heath as a \"village\" even though it has been part of Birmingham for over a century. Its centre at the High Street / Vicarage Road junction has been developed to form an attractive public square which is used as a venue for a monthly [[farmers' market]] and other events.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allsaintscentrekh.co.uk/village-square/ |title=Village Square |author=<!--Not stated--> |website=All Saints Centre Kings Heath |publisher=All Saints Community Development Company |access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 2005, Kings Heath was hit by a major (by European standards) [[Birmingham Tornado (UK)|tornado]] which damaged several shops on High Street and All Saints' Church. The tornado then moved on to damage many houses in [[Balsall Heath]]. There were no fatalities.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Kings Heath Police Station - High Street, Kings Heath (32499828654).jpg|thumb|Kings Heath Police Station]]\nKings Heath has several schools including Colmore Infant, Nursery and Primary School, St. Dunstan's Catholic Primary School, Kings Heath Primary School, [[Kings Heath Boys]], [[Wheelers Lane Technology College]], [[King Edward VI Camp Hill School for Boys]], [[King Edward VI Camp Hill School for Girls]] and [[Bishop Challoner Catholic College]].\n\n==Public transport==\nKings Heath is serviced by [[National Express West Midlands]]' bus routes [[West Midlands bus route 11|11]] (Birmingham Outer Circle), 35 (central Birmingham \u2013 [[Hawkesley]]) and [[West Midlands bus route 50|50]] (central Birmingham \u2013 [[Druids Heath]]).\n\n==Features==\nThe central shopping area runs along High Street and Alcester Road, and the shops include branches of national [[chain store]]s, [[charity shop]]s, supermarkets, electrical retailers and opticians. There are also a number of [[pub]]s, churches and schools on and around High Street.\n\n[[File:UB40 first gig.jpg|thumb|left|Plaque marking UB40's first gig.]]\n\nKings Heath has two parks: [[Kings Heath Park]], which is famous as the setting for the popular [[Associated Television|ATV]] series ''Gardening Today'',<ref name=ATV>{{cite web|first=Roddy |last=Buxton |title=Studio One |url=http://www.transdiffusion.org/emc/studioone/atvs_television.php |accessdate=12 April 2002 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080108142319/http://www.transdiffusion.org/emc/studioone/atvs_television.php |archivedate= 8 January 2008 }}</ref> and Highbury Park, which is adjacent to [[Highbury, Birmingham|Highbury Hall]], a former residence of [[Joseph Chamberlain]]. Kings Heath Park has [[Green Flag Award|\"Green Flag\"]] status. It features a [[Victorian era|Victorian]]-styled [[tea room]] and is the venue for the annual Gardener's Weekend Show, which comes under the [[Royal Horticultural Society]] and is one of the top regional events for gardening enthusiasts to show off their vegetables, floral displays, etc.\n\nThe Hare and Hounds public house, in Kings Heath High Street, was the location of the first concert by [[UB40]] on 9 February 1979, which is commemorated by a [[PRS for Music]] plaque. The pub was rebuilt in 1907, but is Grade II listed, as it has retained many original Art Nouveau internal fixtures.  The pub is still an important local music venue.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hare and Hounds, The Venue|url=http://hareandhoundskingsheath.co.uk/the-venue/|publisher=Hare and Hounds|accessdate=1 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Sport and leisure==\n[[Kings Heath Stadium]] was a [[Greyhound racing|greyhound track]] that existed from the 1920s until its closure in 1971.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tarter|first=P Howard|title=Greyhound Racing Encyclopedia|page =62|year=1949|publisher=Fleet Publishing Company Ltd}}</ref> The site was first developed in 1923 at Alcester Lane's End on the southern outskirts of Kings Heath as the venue for the annual Kings Heath [[Horse Show]]. The ground was converted to include a greyhound track and the first dog race took place in May 1927. After the Horse Show moved elsewhere in the 1960s, the ground was exclusively used for greyhound racing until being permanently closed in 1971. The land was eventually sold for housing development.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsheathhistory.co.uk/content/KH_Horse_Show_Dog_Track.pdf |title=King's Heath Horse Show & Kings Heath Greyhound Stadium |first=Gail |last=Pittaway |work=King's Heath Local History Society |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAn 18-hole [[golf course]] opened in 1926 just to the south of the race track along the Alcester Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mytimeactive.co.uk/golf/cocks-moors-woods-golf-course |title=Cocks Moors Woods Golf Course |work=Mytime Active |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> This is also the site of the modern Cocks Moors Woods [[leisure centre|sports and leisure centre]], the largest of its kind in south Birmingham.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghamleisure.com/cocks_moors_woods |title=Welcome to Cocks Moors Woods Leisure Centre |work=Birmingham Community Leisure Trust |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nKings Heath Baths was an indoor facility on Institute Road that first opened on 15 August 1923. For many years, the swimming pool was drained and floored over during the winter so it could be used as a dance hall, with additional badminton courts also provided.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://www.bathsandwashhouses.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/City-of-Birmingham-Baths-Department-1851-1951.pdf |title=The City of Birmingham Baths Department 1851-1951 |author=J. Moth |year=1951 |publisher=James Upton |page=32}}</ref> The baths closed in 1987 and the building was subsequently demolished.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moseleyb13.com/2016/08/04/lost-moseley-last-splash-part-one-lidos-baths/ |title=Lost Moseley: \u2018Last Splash?\u2019 Part One \u2013 Lidos & Baths |date=4 August 2016 |first=Mark  |last=Baxter |work=Moseley B13 magazine |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Kingsway Cinema opened on High Street in March 1925 and remained open for more than fifty years until its closure in May 1980. The cinema was later converted into a [[Bingo (United Kingdom)|bingo hall]], first run by Essoldo Bingo, then [[Gala Bingo]], but eventually closed in 2007. The building was largely destroyed by a fire on 17 September 2011.<ref name=KHLHS_KingswayCinema>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsheathhistory.co.uk/content/Kingsway.pdf |title=Kingsway Cinema Story |first=Bob |last=Blackham |date=July 2019 |work=King's Heath Local History Society |access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> It was auctioned off in 2016 to a local building development company<ref name=Mail_KingswayCinema>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/business/new-plans-restore-historic-fire-14169674 |title=New plans to restore historic former Kings Heath cinema |first=Tamlyn |last=Jones |newspaper=[[Birmingham Mail]] |date=18 January 2018|access-date=12 October 2019}}</ref> and demolition work was carried out at the rear of the building in early 2018.<ref name=KHLHS_KingswayCinema /> The [[Listed building#Locally listed buildings|Grade A locally listed]] [[facade]] at the front was largely unaffected by the 2011 fire and the redevelopment plans include restoring this to its former glory.<ref name=Mail_KingswayCinema />\n\n==Notable residents==\n;People born in Kings Heath\n* [[Tommy Green (footballer, born 1873)|Tommy Green]] (1873\u20131921), footballer who played for [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]]\n* Sydney S. Guy (1885\u20131971), founder of [[Guy Motors]]\n* [[Albert Gardner]] (1887\u20131923), footballer who played for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n* [[Frank Bowden (footballer)|Frank Bowden]] (1904\u2013?), footballer who played for Birmingham City and [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]]\n* [[Edna Iles]] (1905\u20132003), classical pianist\n* [[Jim Roberts (architect)|Jim Roberts]] (born 1922), architect whose works included the [[Rotunda (Birmingham)|Rotunda]] in central Birmingham\n* [[Peter Aldis]] (1927\u20132008), footballer who played for [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n* [[Ann Jones (tennis)|Ann Jones]] (born 1938),<ref name=KHLHS_famous>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingsheathhistory.co.uk/fame.htm |title=Famous former residents of King's Heath |work=King's Heath Local History Society |access-date=11 October 2019}}</ref> tennis player who won seven [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] Championships\n* [[Martin Barre]] (born 1946), guitarist for [[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]]\n* [[Dave Latchford]] (born 1948), footballer who played for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n* [[Bob Latchford]] (born 1951), footballer who played for Birmingham City, [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] and [[England national football team|England]]\n* [[Peter Latchford]] (born 1952), footballer who played for [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] and [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n* [[Toyah Willcox]] (born 1958), musician and actress\n* [[Dave Linney]] (born 1961), footballer who played for [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]]\n* [[Gary Childs]] (born 1964), footballer for [[Walsall F.C.|Walsall]] and [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]]\n* [[Kevin Ashley]] (born 1968), footballer who played for [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] and [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]\n* [[Laura Mvula]] (born 1986), soul singer/songwriter\n\n;Notable residents\n* [[J. R. R. Tolkien]] (1892\u20131973),<ref name=KHLHS_famous /> moved to Kings Heath to live with his grandparents in 1895\n* [[Anthony E. Pratt]] (1903\u20131994),<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/plaque-erected-kings-heath-cluedo-1325186|title=Plaque to be erected for Kings Heath Cluedo inventor Anthony Pratt|newspaper=Birmingham Mail|author=Mike Lockley|date=17 February 2013}}</ref> inventor of the board game ''[[Cluedo]]''\n* [[Tommy Godwin (cyclist born 1920)|Tommy Godwin]] (1920\u20132012),<ref name=KHLHS_famous /> international cyclist who ran a cycle shop in Kings Heath from 1950 to 1986\n* [[Judith Cutler]] (born 1946), crime fiction writer\n* [[Stuart Linnell]] MBE (born 1947 in Northfield, Birmingham), radio and TV presenter\n* [[Trevor Burton]] (born 1949), guitarist and founding member of [[The Move]]\n* [[Paul Dyson]] (born 1959), footballer for [[Coventry City F.C.|Coventry City]] and [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] who ran a sports shop in Kings Heath after his retirement\n* [[Joe Lycett]] (born 1988),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://birmingham.livingmag.co.uk/joe-lycett/ |title=Joe Lycett |work=Birmingham Living magazine |access-date=2020-02-08}}</ref> British comedian\n\n==In popular culture==\n[[File:Church Musicians window, King's Heath, Birmingham.JPG|thumb|The church musicians window; Kings Heath Methodist Church; featuring Bach, Charles Wesley, Handel and the local organist Leslie Wright]]\nThe 2011 musical film ''[[Turbulence (2011 film)|Turbulence]]'' was shot in the area, with much of the film's action taking place in the Hare & Hounds pub.<ref>{{cite news |last=Suart |first=Paul |date=15 July 2011 |title=Kings Heath film maker turns to bike power for new movie |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/local-news/kings-heath-film-maker-turns-157823 |work=Birmingham Mail |publisher=Trinity Mirror Midlands |access-date=8 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe 2013 song \"Green Garden\" by Birmingham born [[Laura Mvula]] is an elegy to her home in Kings Heath.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.birminghampost.co.uk/whats-on/music/|title=Latest Birmingham and West Midlands news on Food & Drink, Nostalgia, Fashion,|website=www.birminghampost.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nThe BBC documentary ''Fighting For Air'', about suburban air pollution, was filmed in Kings Heath in 2017 and broadcast on BBC2 on 10 January 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kingsheathforum.org.uk/2018/01/08/fighting-for-air-bbc2-documentary-broadcast-10-january-2017/|title=\u2018Fighting For Air\u2019 BBC2 documentary broadcast 10 January 2018|work=Kings Heath Residents' Forum|date=8 January 2018|access-date=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Moseley and Kings Heath (ward)|Moseley and Kings Heath ward]]\n* [[Brandwood (ward)|Brandwood ward]]\n* [[Ritz Ballroom, Kings Heath]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/ Birmingham City Council]\n*[http://www.birmingham.gov.uk/cs/Satellite?c=Page&childpagename=Lib-Kings-Heath%2FPageLayout&cid=1223092586607&pagename=BCC%2FCommon%2FWrapper%2FWrapper History of Kings Heath]\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.asp?sheetid=10125&ox=2349&oy=2425&zm=4 1884 Ordnance Survey map of King's Heath]\n*[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/mapsheet.asp?sheetid=9257&ox=1400&oy=1275&zm=2&czm=2&x=189&y=177 1887 Ordnance Survey map of King's Heath]\n\n{{Areas of Birmingham}}\n\n[[Category:Areas of Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n", "name_user": "Lolalima33", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kings_Heath"}
